A branch is like a separate version of your project.

  You use a branch when you want to work on something new without messing up your main project.

  Think of it like this:

    main branch = the safe working version

    new branch = the testing/work area


When you have a main working project and if you want to make changes you make a second branch

  If it works, you can later add it back into your main project.

  If it breaks, your main project is still safe.

A branch is a safe place to experiment.

  You can try new code without destroying the version that already works.



Where to find branches:

  On GitHub, branches are inside your repository page.

  Then look near the top-left of the files.

  You should see something like:

    main ▼

      That dropdown is the branch menu.

      Click it, and you can see your branches.

